评论概述: Affordable and great quality Alternative/Goth/Punk bracelets

This "Punk" Bracelet set is pretty cool. There are individual bands with square studs and mini spikes, and a larger 3-band bracelet that has more studs, a chain, and some smaller round studs.  This design definitely hit the look I was hoping for, and the price for the bracelet set wasn't bad.  The bracelets are better quality than a costume-only set; the bands are thick imitation leather, the studs attached properly, etc. These bracelets will eventually crack and break, but they'll last longer than anything you could find at Spirit Hallowe’en, and its unlikely you could find any that were true leather without paying three times as much.  As I said above, I love these. I wear at least one about three times a week.

There are three adjustable bracelets in this set to allow for a better fit. The faux leather is thin and light to wear. The two smaller bracelets have silver hardware that stands out well against the black faux leather. The layered bracelet seems to have black or gunmetal studs which do not stand out as well. The chain on that bracelet seems cheap/delicate, so be careful putting it on or taking it off. The set has a nice punk or rocker vie and can be worn individually or stacked.

I bought these for my teenage daughter who recently started getting into punk and metal.  These are surprisingly good quality considering the price. They're really cute and definitely help complete the punk look. I was into punk and metal as a teenager myself and had several spiked bands. I can tell you from experience that these are no where near what the old style ones were like. My old bands (which I still have some of them) were made of thick, genuine leather and had real (pointed) spikes. These are made of a nice looking fake leather or possibly a very thin much weaker leather and the spikes are rounded off. This definitely reduces the Injury risk which as a father makes me happy, but it does rduce the old fashion hyper aggressive punk charm. That said, 3 bands for under $10 is a great deal. My bands used to run anywhere from around $30-$100 each in the 80s.
